PN,41806
SC,0006
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F418A1779393955
OL,3,CRoses bloom 'weeks early' as climate
OL,4,Cchange upends flowering patterns
OL,6,FAt Chartwell, gardens and outdoor
OL,7,Fmanager Christopher Lane said this
OL,8,Fspring was a clear indication of how
OL,9,Fthe changing climate was affecting
OL,10,Fgardens.
OL,12,FHe said: "The lack of cold snaps has
OL,13,Fgiven plants an early boost,
OL,14,Faccelerating growth across the garden.
OL,16,F"We saw our first rose in flower as
OL,17,Fearly as March, something that would
OL,18,Fnormally come much later."
OL,26,@tD@JOUxD@AOUzD@ZO]
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G6/9
OL,2,W,.!" ,.!+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,
OL,23,TppppppppppppppppppGsource: itv.com/news
OL,24,ANext PageBS-SE Eng NewsCThis DayFReg TV
FL,419,410,120,260,000,100
PN,41807
SC,0007
CT,2,C
PS,c008
OL,0,        ECIMSBWebfax 1   F418A1779393955
OL,3,CRoses bloom 'weeks early' as climate
OL,4,Cchange upends flowering patterns
OL,6,FSam Brown, senior gardener at Buckland
OL,7,FAbbey, said roses were coming into
OL,8,Fflower two to three weeks earlier than
OL,9,Ftraditionally expected, and added that
OL,10,Fshorter dormancy periods, more pests
OL,11,Fsurviving the winter and increasing
OL,12,Fsummer drought were all creating
OL,13,Fchallenges.
OL,15,FHe said: "We're responding by
OL,16,Fimproving soil health, selecting
OL,17,Fresilient varieties and using
OL,18,Ftechniques like mulching and
OL,19,Funderplanting to retain moisture."
OL,26,@wD@JOU{D@bO]
OL,1,W~s1x0~s1~s hw1~k4~c1 hw}h7}j7}   G7/9
OL,2,W,.!" ,.!+, "-$/*%+.!+,*%/*%/*-'T(,,,,,,
